metadata.name: Zero-player game #132
metadata.description:
The pattern is endless and doesn't loop. It is deterministic: even if you scroll a mile away and then return, you will find each pixel exactly where it was. Give it a try!

When I was young, It was intimidating to think about space because it was endless. I felt like I'm completely dissolving in it and turning into zero.

I was getting older and exploring the world around me. What seemed large and complex turned out to be the result of the interaction of simple elements. Even the infinite Universe can be decomposed and understood.

“Zero-player game” is a cellular automaton through which I explore the concept of infinity and emergence. The game starts with a surface covered by random cells. Over six iterations the image becomes more complex as the cells divide and change their colors according to a set of thirty two rules.

More information about the project at https://ivandianov.com/zero-player-game/

- Swipe or use arrow keys to navigate.
- Add ?lat=100500&lon=100500 to URL and teleport to a distant location.
- Press “S” to save a picture.

metadata.name: RULES (for Elementary Cellular Automata) #64
metadata.description:
An important element of generative art is emergence. The most famous algorithm for this is probably Cellular Automata (CA).

However, numerous generative artists have created works using CA, which has lost its visual freshness and is like chewing gum that has lost its taste.

Although it is such a classic algorithm, adding my own little ideas to it and finding a new "flavor" is the reason why I code.

Here, the subject is 1D Elementary Cellular Automata, the simplest of all cellular automata. 1D Elementary Cellular Automata has 256 different rules, which change the shapes produced. This work aims to create more complex shapes by randomly selecting some of those rules and placing multiple of them on the screen.

The on/off of the CA cell is often likened to the behavior of living creatures.As of 2022, in the country where I live, prices are rising, wages are not increasing, and COVID-19 has not yet ended. I created this work with the image of people at the mercy of these various rules.

---

Screen click: Change rules
S key: Save png
L key: Show/hide grid

metadata.name: Linetract #90
metadata.description:
Art unites people, the same is also true with Artists.

"Linetract" is a collaborative work of two different artist: @Jolie__Michel and @Uniray_net 
Different backgrounds, different styles, same passion for creativity and Art!

"Linetract" is an abstract composition of simple shapes forms and colors, merged into a final minimal and hopefully aesthetic interesting result :)

CONTROLS

KEYS:

- 1-4: Set resolution from 1x to 4x of the current dimension (possibly slower performance in higher values)
- S: Save a png file with the current resolution

Made with p5js and custom shaders

Collaboration project by @Jolie__Michel and @Uniray_net
© January 2023

metadata.name: Dots #166
metadata.description:
Titled as a play with colors and shapes created from dots, Dots started as a collection on Objkt, extended to 8bidou and had new developments in Exchange Art. It was a dream to be able to make a collection of Dots on Fxhash, now it finally happened. Initially we only had 1 color palette, however, to create more variety, this project has 7 color palettes. To create the palettes we chose 5 famous artists to honor, including Peter Halley, Max Bill, Piet Mondrian, Sophie Taeuber and Lygia Clark, in addition to the palettes created by us. The project has several grids and some new possibilities in addition to the pieces already created on other platforms. It is with great pride and joy that we present this project made with great affection. Enjoy!

Press [S] to save a image

metadata.name: Hypericum #239
metadata.description:
This system translates color into movement. A swarm of drawing particles, like virtual pencils, are guided by the color values of the pixels in an input image. The formulas performing the conversion put into play many parameters. The space of possibilities of the system is enormous, the variety of drawings endless. 256 is just a small arbitrary sample. 

This work can be seen as a playful reflection on the concept of “style”, which is so essential to our ideas about art and (human) artists. This short program can paint the same image on infinitely many “styles” – each of them reducible to a simple combination of mathematical parameters. 

The input image is a photo of a yellow hypericum flower I took during a holiday in the Argentinean Patagonia, near Bariloche, in 2016.

Better on landscape format (optimal ratio is 3:2) > on your computer, [open live]
Press [s] to download capture.

Made by Leonardo Solaas
TW > @solaas
IG > @leonardo_solaas
WWW > solaas.com.ar

metadata.name: GeoRhythms #9
metadata.description:
**"GeoRhythms" is a compound word formed from "Geo," derived from "Geometric" or "Geometry," referring to geometric shapes, and "Rhythms," which means patterns or sequences of movement. In this context, the name "GeoRhythms" might suggest geometric forms found in nature that are combined with a specific rhythm or pattern. This name can represent a fusion of geometry and nature harmonized with a sense of rhythm.
In this project, my endeavor was to present a unique perspective of nature through abstract forms. I hope you all enjoy this project.

metadata.name: Anfractuous #20
metadata.description: The title is quite literally a visual description of the work, as anfractuous means: characterized by windings and turnings; sinuous; circuitous. With this project I aimed to strike a balance between easily recognizable smooth large scale forms and the small fragmented details that populate these forms.

metadata.name: Obliques #134
metadata.description:
Obliques are a reinterpretation of Parallels, a collection of AI generated color fields by Marc Maurer. Many of the pieces in that collection are CC0, which basically means they can be reused for other projects, like this one.

Obliques takes artifacts from Parallels and uses them as brushes, painting slices of the original image on the canvas in a (hopefully) pleasant, chaotic way.

About 10% will be "Glitched".

The "Source Material" property will tell you the name of piece that it is using.

You can see Marc Maurer's Parallels project here:
https://objkt.com/collection/KT1TiSEcASGD19SW8bmqrqgSgCBkwXqDdTJ1

Obliques are also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

G : Toggle Grain
M : Toggle Matte
S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

metadata.name: caravans #161
metadata.description:
This piece is inspired by Paul Klee's 'Zwei Kamele und ein Esel' (Two camels and a donkey), abacuses and excessive shopping sprees.

An anonymous caravan makes its way through abstract deserts, carrying their semi-brutalist cargo towards an unknown destination.

All primary proceeds go to the Processing foundation.

Happy birthday fxhash!

Written in JavaScript, rendering to Canvas.
